<br>
I havnt read the EQ2 update yet but, heres my two cents on item wear<br>
<br>
- Item wear, all around is a great idea I think. I'd say the best implementation of it so far is probably in Ultima Online however, this is largly due to (atleast when I last played, the damn game is allways changing), the near-best armour you could use was a Grand Master crafted set, minus rares like deamon armour, vanq, armour of hardening, etc, and for the most part, the &quot;good&quot; armour could be gotten via normal gameplay largly, and it entered the game at such a rate that most players got a piece now and then, and trades people would collect it and have it on their vendors.<br>
<br>
Losing a full set of armour of hardening or whatever the best while a bitch, wasnt earth-shattering like losing a full set of it in EQ, and hell..death in UO wasnt that bad, pretty easy to get all your stuff back, and if it wore out, *shrug* chances are you had a few backup sets allready.<br>
<br>
With that being said, for item-wear to work effectivly, people need to be able to get armour upgrades/backups/etc via &quot;normal&quot; game play (ie: not sit and camp all day). And the baseline armour in which people are balanced for needs to be READILY available. Sure, have great/rare/powerfull items but dont balance it so people NEED those items to be effective.<br>
<br>
Thinking in EQ terms of years ago : balance it so a warrior in crafted armour is &quot;balanced&quot;, not a warrior in full cobolt. Sure, if hes in cobolt he'll be better, but its not needed to be considered effective.<br>
<br>
I am a big fan of item wear, if the speed of items that wear is reasonable, and if the itemization in the game is done in such a way that it is NOT tedious to the player, but enough to get items out of the economy at a reasonable rate. People shouldnt be having to run back to town to repair their armour every 2 or 3 hours of play.<br>
<br>
Ideally, it'd be nice if armour didnt need repaired/etc for lets say, every 20-25 hours of actuall &quot;play&quot; time (so, for avg joe blow who plays 5 hours a day, has to repair about once a week)<br>
<br>
and, shrug, tossing numbers out of my ass, if after like the 5th repair, it can no longer be reparied any more (so, little over a month), though 'normal' game play (ie: not camping), said player should allready have a replacmeet item or two readily available to them so they dont need to go out of their way to camp gear. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kinanifarslayer>Kinani Farslayer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/10/03 6:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26846.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Actually I hope everything they are touting is put in exactly as is. That way the game will be an annoying piece o crap that other mmporg designers look at as full of things not to do ingame P. The key in any future mmporg imo will be to find a way to let people interact and form friendships forged in adventuring togther. When EQ sucked and it often did the friends I have ingame still made it great. Who among us has not shown up and made a significant contribution in helping a friend get epiced or cr from some nasty place etc etc.Riding the edge of what your guild,group or friends were capable of and coming out on top with items in hand were some of the best times in EQ. Farming to gear a guild up for the next step built cohesion and trust in your friends and guildies. <br>
